Also, as general advice, start with getting the broad body shape first, the torso especially, then work on the extremities. The rest will be down to understanding good topology practices.

Anonymous Sat 06 Apr 2024 15:57:04 No.64660769 Report
Quoted By: >>64660866
>>64660604
Blender has a built in addon called Loop Tools (you can find and activate it in the addons panel)

This gives you a number of functions you can use when in edit mode on a mesh. Space makes the distance between the selected vertices the same, and relax relaxes the selected vertices, so kind of a smooth. Both of these help make more even and organic models while polymodeling. The other functions are also really useful, and you can read more about them in the documentation or people's tutorials.
